      {
        "id": 2331572,
        "name": "Faryan Amir-Ghassemi",
        "username": "Faryan_Amir-Ghassemi",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/faryan_amir-ghassemi/{size}/824_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-01-07T22:33:51.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Had these two bottles while hunkered down during the freeze.  The Huet was pretty monolithic two or three years ago but is begining to unclench.  Really lovely depth, adding that wonderful waxiness that you get from Huet Chenin.  The sec version is often my favorite even though the demis can be superior for aging curves.  It still has the grip and staying power but is begining to add the complexity you are seeing in spades with the 06s and 07s.  Drink or hold.</p>\n<p>The 2012 Puffeney Savagnin is really backward.  Needed about 1.5 hrs of air to blow off the intense nutty/sherry flavors and round.  It\u2019s still big and primary but can be pleasurable, especially with food and air.  A 20 year wine and some of the best Savagnin outside of Overnoy to my palate.</p>\n<p>Cheers</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T02:29:37.163Z",
